04525nam a2200649Ia 9780674028876DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20092001mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740288767 a10.4159/97806740288762doi  a(DE-B1597)574420  a(OCoLC)1257324295  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a306.451 aBrown, James Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWho Rules in Science? :bAn Opinionated Guide to the Wars /cJames Robert Brown. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2009] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tWHO RULES IN SCIENCE -- t1. Scenes from the Science Wars -- t2. The Scientific Experience -- t3. How We Got to Where We Are -- t4. The Nihilist Wing of Social Constructivism -- t5. Three Key Terms -- t6. The Naturalist Wing of Social Constructivism -- t7. The Role of Reason -- t8. The Democratization of Science -- t9. Science with a Social Agenda -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat if something as seemingly academic as the so-called science wars were to determine how we live?This eye-opening book reveals how little we've understood about the ongoing pitched battles between the sciences and the humanities--and how much may be at stake. James Brown's starting point is C. P. Snow's famous book, Two Cultures and the Scientific Revolution, which set the terms for the current debates. But that little book did much more than identify two new, opposing cultures, Brown contends: It also claimed that scientists are better qualified than nonscientists to solve political and social problems. In short, the true significance of Snow's treatise was its focus on the question of who should rule--a question that remains vexing, pressing, and politically explosive today.In Who Rules in Science? Brown takes us through the various engagements in the science wars--from the infamous "Sokal affair" to angry confrontations over the nature of evidence, the possibility of objectivity, and the methods of science--to show how the contested terrain may be science, but the prize is political: Whoever wins the science wars will have an unprecedented influence on how we are governed.Brown provides the most comprehensive and balanced assessment yet of the science wars. He separates the good arguments from the bad, and exposes the underlying message: Science and social justice are inextricably linked. His book is essential reading if we are to understand the forces making and remaking our world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aPolitique scientifique et technique. 0aScience and state. 0aSciencexSocial aspects. 0aSciencesxAspect social. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674028876?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674028876423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674028876/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles